I'll provide clean, production-ready code examples demonstrating security best practices in different languages:

1. Python - Secure Database Operations
```python
import sqlite3
from contextlib import closing

def get_user(db_path, user_id):
    """Safe database query using parameterized statements"""
    with closing(sqlite3.connect(db_path)) as conn:
        conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row
        with closing(conn.cursor()) as cursor:
            cursor.execute("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", (user_id,))
            return cursor.fetchone()
```

2. JavaScript - Input Sanitization
```javascript
// Safe HTML output
function sanitizeInput(input) {
    const div = document.createElement('div');
    div.textContent = input;
    return div.innerHTML;
}

// Safe user content display
function displayUserComment(comment) {
    const safeComment = sanitizeInput(comment);
    document.getElementById('comment-box').innerHTML = safeComment;
}
```

3. Java - Secure Password Handling
```java
import java.security.SecureRandom;
import java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;
import java.security.spec.KeySpec;
import javax.crypto.SecretKeyFactory;
import javax.crypto.spec.PBEKeySpec;

public class PasswordHasher {
    private static final int ITERATIONS = 65536;
    private static final int KEY_LENGTH = 256;
    
    public static byte[] generateSalt() {
        SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();
        byte[] salt = new byte[16];
        random.nextBytes(salt);
        return salt;
    }
    
    public static byte[] hashPassword(String password, byte[] salt) 
            throws NoSuchAlgorithmException, InvalidKeySpecException {
        KeySpec spec = new PBEKeySpec(
            password.toCharArray(), 
            salt, 
            ITERATIONS, 
            KEY_LENGTH
        );
        SecretKeyFactory factory = SecretKeyFactory.getInstance("PBKDF2WithHmacSHA256");
        return factory.generateSecret(spec).getEncoded();
    }
}
```